{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17592931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17592931"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:20:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:20:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15284"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15284"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.81,0.11,0,0,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7975"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69025"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7975","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7975"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15284"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54482"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"8478"},{"type":"tags","id":"8479"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19403"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19406"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69025"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine check-up. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is a non-smoker and drinks alcohol occasionally. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. During the consultation, she asks about liver function and anatomy, particularly the role of the sinusoids and the space of Disse in the liver.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements best describes the structure and function of liver sinusoids?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sinusoids are lined by fenestrated endothelial cells and Kupffer cells","The space of Disse prevents direct contact between blood and hepatocytes","Hepatocyte microvilli reduce the surface area for absorption","Blood cells freely enter the space of Disse","Portal blood bypasses the sinusoids to reach central veins"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe liver has a unique microscopic structure that facilitates its metabolic and detoxifying functions. \u003Cstrong\u003ESinusoids are lined by fenestrated endothelial cells and Kupffer cells\u003C/strong\u003E which are specialised liver macrophages. The fenestrations allow plasma components to enter the space of Disse while retaining blood cells within the sinusoid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe space of Disse prevents direct contact between blood and hepatocytes\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because this space actually facilitates exchange between blood and hepatocytes through the fenestrated endothelium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatocyte microvilli reduce the surface area for absorption\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Hepatocytes have numerous microvilli projecting into the space of Disse specifically to increase the surface area available for absorption and secretion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood cells freely enter the space of Disse\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While plasma can enter through the fenestrations in the endothelium, cellular components of blood remain within the sinusoids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPortal blood bypasses the sinusoids to reach central veins\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Blood from both the portal vein and hepatic artery must flow through the sinusoids before reaching the central veins, allowing for metabolic exchange with hepatocytes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The space of Disse is the perisinusoidal space between the sinusoidal endothelium and hepatocytes.","Hepatocytes have microvilli that project into the space of Disse to increase absorption from the plasma.","Sinusoids are lined by fenestrated endothelial cells and Kupffer cells, which are liver macrophages."],"references":["Nightingale, J. M. (2012). Applied anatomy and physiology of the gastrointestinal tract (GIT). Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book: Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book, 45","Podolsky, D. K., Camilleri, M., Fitz, J. G., Kalloo, A. N., Shanahan, F., \u0026 Wang, T. C. (Eds.). (2015). Yamada\u0027s textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54482"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15284"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54482","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54482"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T20:40:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T20:43:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7975"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69025"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags",